                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d101">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Conference/62</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">British Embassy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum of Conversation With Mr. Mallet, British Chargé
                        d’Affaires, October</hi> 19, 1937</p>
                <p>In discussing with Mr. Mallet the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of October
                    18th, which the British Chargé d’Affaires had been good enough to bring to the
                    attention of the Government of the United States concerning a further meeting of
                    the Advisory Committee, Mr. Wilson stated that, since the Government of the
                    United States was not a member of the League of Nations, it had refrained
                    scrupulously at any time from endeavoring to influence League bodies in such
                    action as they might choose to adopt. It is to be remembered that the American
                    representative sitting on the Advisory Committee does so without the right to
                    vote.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-19">October 19,
                            1937</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
